                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/east-564" class="program-course-title">
              EAST 564 Structures of Modernity: Japan (3 credits)              <!---->            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-22236" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: East Asian Studies (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/607">Faculty of Arts</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      Asian Language &amp; Literature              : This course explores relations between some of the principal sites which structure the experience of "modernity" in Japan (and elsewhere) - from bodies and cities, to the urban context in general. Along with general approaches (e.g. the idea of everyday life; questions of time), specific topics may include speed, music, architecture, crime, etc.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Winter 2015          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:                        Yuriko Furuhata (Winter)                  </p>

    
          <ul class="catalog-notes">
              <li>Prerequisite (Undergraduate): Any East Asian Studies course above the introductory level, or permission of the instructor</li>
            </ul>
      </div>

  </div> <!-- /.node -->
              </div>
            </div>
